<text>
<body>
<div>
<pb facs="#facs_1" n="1" xml:id="img_0001"/>
<ab facs="#facs_1_r1">
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l2" n="N001"/>
<placeName ref="#place-7002482">Baghdad</placeName>
<choice>
<abbr>
<date when="1921-08-18">Aug </date>
</abbr>
<expan>August</expan>
</choice>
<date when="1921-08-18">18</date>
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l1" n="N002"/>
<add place="in-line">Received </add>
<add place="in-line">
<date when="1921-09-30">30 </date>
</add>
<choice>
<abbr>
<add place="in-line">
<date when="1921-09-30">Sep </date>
</add>
</abbr>
<expan>September</expan>
</choice>
<add place="in-line">
<date when="1921-09-30">1921</date>
</add>
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l3" n="N003"/>
<add place="below">1921</add>
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l4" n="N004"/>
Darling
<persName ref="#person-EH006">Father</persName>
. We have had rather an uneventful week. The referendum
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l5" n="N005"/>
is finished + we are only waiting for the last of the signed papers
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l6" n="N006"/>
to come in from the provinces, after which
<persName ref="#person-EH001">Faisal</persName>
will be proclaimed
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l7" n="N007"/>
King without delay. With one exception he has been elected
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l8" n="N008"/>
unanimously but in a great number of cases - more than
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l9" n="N009"/>
half the country I should say - the people have added a
<choice>
<corr>rider</corr>
<sic>ryder</sic>
</choice>
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l10" n="N010"/>
of their own, saying that they agree to his being King as long as he
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l11" n="N011"/>
maintains friendly relations with the British
<choice>
<abbr>Govt</abbr>
<expan>Government</expan>
</choice>
, or as long as
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l12" n="N012"/>
he accepts the British protection. The additions are differently
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l13" n="N013"/>
worded but they all come to the same thing. The one exception
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l14" n="N014"/>
is
<placeName ref="#place-1001115">Kirkuk</placeName>
. There, as you know, the town population is Turcoman
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l15" n="N015"/>
+ the village population Kurd. Neither want Arab rule + among
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l16" n="N016"/>
the Turks there has been a good deal of Turkish, anti-
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l17" n="N017"/>
British propaganda. Two of the quarters of Kirkuk town have
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l18" n="N018"/>
asked for a Turkish ruler. The Kurds are not anti-British;
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l19" n="N019"/>
they want a Kurdish independent state under our protection,
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l20" n="N020"/>
but what they mean by that neither they nor anyone
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l21" n="N021"/>
else knows. For they emphatically refuse to be connected
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l22" n="N022"/>
in any way with the Kurdish province of
<placeName ref="#place-1001109">Sulaimani</placeName>
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l23" n="N023"/>
which before the coming of Faisal had already
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l24" n="N024"/>
voted itself out of the
<placeName ref="#place-1000118">'Iraq</placeName>
state. So much for
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l25" n="N025"/>
Kurdish nationalism of which you may possibly hear
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l26" n="N026"/>
a lot of tosh talked in the next few months, unless
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l27" n="N027"/>
indeed
<persName ref="#person-EH002">Sir Percy</persName>
succeeds in inducing Kirkuk to listen
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l28" n="N028"/>
to reason.
<placeName ref="#place-1001311">Arbil</placeName>
+ all the Kurdish districts round
<placeName ref="#place-7002471">Mosul</placeName>
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l29" n="N029"/>
have come in, realizing that their political + economic
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l30" n="N030"/>
welfare is bound up with Mosul. They have bargained for +
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l31" n="N031"/>
will obtain certain privileges, such as Kurdish officials. Some
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l32" n="N032"/>
ask that all the teaching in the schools should be in Kurdish,
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l33" n="N033"/>
a reasonable request if it weren't for the fact that Kurdish
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l34" n="N034"/>
can barely be called a written language + that there
<lb facs="#facs_1_r1l35" n="N035"/>
aren't any Kurdish teachers + those can only be trained
</ab>
<pb facs="#facs_2" n="2" xml:id="img_0002"/>
<ab facs="#facs_2_r1">
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l1" n="N001"/>
in Arabic, for there are no Kurdish books at all.
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l2" n="N002"/>
Dunya! it's an odd world.
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l3" n="N003"/>
The difficulty this week has been the climate. Not
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l4" n="N004"/>
that it has been so very hot - never over 119 I
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l5" n="N005"/>
think - but it has been quite still with a lightly
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l6" n="N006"/>
clouded sky. When you get up in the morning + see a
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l7" n="N007"/>
cloud your heart sinks, for it means a close oppressive
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l8" n="N008"/>
day like the half hour before a thunderstorm carried to
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l9" n="N009"/>
the Nth, There were a couple of days at the beginning of the
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l10" n="N010"/>
week when I seriously considered whether I could bear it.
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l11" n="N011"/>
Now it's better.
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l12" n="N012"/>
It was partly the climate + partly its our misdemeanours
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l13" n="N013"/>
which made me fall foul of one of the local newspapers.
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l14" n="N014"/>
<seg type="editorialNote-target-text">
The Dijlah
<note type="editorial">Dijlah refers to an Iraqi current affairs publication.</note>
</seg>
is edited by a young ass who is
<choice>
<corr>against</corr>
<sic>agin</sic>
</choice>
everybody,
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l15" n="N015"/>
no matter whom. And the idiot public of the coffee shops,
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l16" n="N016"/>
seeing him to be in universal opposition read his rag
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l17" n="N017"/>
eagerly in the hope that they will find him in
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l18" n="N018"/>
opposition to us. He is by way of being the pure
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l19" n="N019"/>
high-minded Arab patriot + he demonstrates this by
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l20" n="N020"/>
publishing all the news of Turkish successes which
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l21" n="N021"/>
happened 6 weeks ago without dreaming of giving a
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l22" n="N022"/>
date. Finally the clouds + the fact that on one + the
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l23" n="N023"/>
same day he announced that the Greeks were escaping
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l24" n="N024"/>
in ships from
<placeName ref="#place-7002543">Ismir</placeName>
while the
<seg type="editorialNote-target-text">
Reuters
<note type="editorial">Bell may be using this term to refer to published news in general (in reference to the Reuters news organisation)</note>
</seg>
in another Arab
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l25" n="N025"/>
paper related that the Turks were evacuating
<placeName ref="#place-1001101">Angora</placeName>
,
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l26" n="N026"/>
were more than I could bear. You understand the
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l27" n="N027"/>
public here hates the Greek successes + applauds anyone
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l28" n="N028"/>
who talks of Turkish victories; moreover they buy his paper.
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l29" n="N029"/>
In principle I feel the same. I don't the least want to
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l30" n="N030"/>
see the Greeks in
<placeName ref="#place-7002294">Asia Minor</placeName>
;
<choice>
<corr>space</corr>
<sic>I</sic>
</choice>
there's no settlement
<lb facs="#facs_2_r1l31" n="N031"/>
that way. But my business now is to set up
</ab>
<pb facs="#facs_3" n="3" xml:id="img_0003"/>
<ab facs="#facs_3_r1">
<lb facs="#facs_3_r1l1" n="N001"/>
2
<lb facs="#facs_3_r1l2" n="N002"/>
an Arab state in
<placeName ref="#place-1000118">Mesopotamia</placeName>
+ the only visible enemy
<lb facs="#facs_3_r1l3" n="N003"/>
is the
<seg type="editorialNote-target-text">
Kamalists
<note type="editorial">Bell is likely referring to Turkish Nationalists, under the leadership of Mustapha Kemal Atatürk.</note>
</seg>
allied with the Bolshevists. They have
<lb facs="#facs_3_r1l4" n="N004"/>
at this very moment occupied with a force of 60
<lb facs="#facs_3_r1l5" n="N005"/>
men a bit of our mountain country north of
<placeName ref="#place-1001311">Arbil</placeName>
<lb facs="#facs_3_r1l6" n="N006"/>
+ set up Turkish
<choice>
<abbr>Govt</abbr>
<expan>Government</expan>
</choice>
there. The thing is a pure
<lb facs="#facs_3_r1l7" n="N007"/>
farce, but we haven't troops to send up into those
<lb facs="#facs_3_r1l8" n="N008"/>
mountains; we can only operate by air which isn't
<lb facs="#facs_3_r1l9" n="N009"/>
enough; so we have to let it alone, with the result
<lb facs="#facs_3_r1l10" n="N010"/>
that every miscreant along the frontier begins to sit
<lb facs="#facs_3_r1l11" n="N011"/>
up + take notice.
<persName ref="#person-EH011">Ja'far</persName>
sent in to say that while
<lb facs="#facs_3_r1l12" n="N012"/>
the Dijlah was publishing telegrams announcing Turkish
<lb facs="#facs_3_r1l13" n="N013"/>
victories he could get no recruits for the Arab army.
<lb facs="#facs_3_r1l14" n="N014"/>
Peoples' minds were disturbed + they began to talk
<lb facs="#facs_3_l" n="N015"/>
of the possibility of the Turks come back! That's what
<lb facs="#facs_3_r1l18" n="N016"/>
they are like in the East - don't I know it.
<lb facs="#facs_3_l_712" n="N017"/>
Well, then I had to do something, clouds or no
<lb facs="#facs_3_r1l21" n="N018"/>
clouds. The editor of the Dijlah is a close friend of
<lb facs="#facs_3_r1l22" n="N019"/>
another young ass, the son of
<persName ref="#person-EH015">'Abdul Majid Shawi</persName>
.
<lb facs="#facs_3_r1l23" n="N020"/>
The good old 'Abdul Majid worships his son but he
<lb facs="#facs_3_r1l24" n="N021"/>
bitterly deplores his silly obstinate ways which he
<lb facs="#facs_3_r1l25" n="N022"/>
can do nothing to amend. I sent for Abdul Majid,
<lb facs="#facs_3_r1l26" n="N023"/>
pointed out that this was past a joke + dictated
<lb facs="#facs_3_r1l27" n="N024"/>
a paragraph in which I stated the actual position
<lb facs="#facs_3_r1l28" n="N025"/>
of Turks + Greeks, taken from the latest Intelligence
<lb facs="#facs_3_r1l29" n="N026"/>
cable from our military authorities in
<placeName ref="#place-7002473">Constantinople</placeName>
.
<lb facs="#facs_3_r1l30" n="N027"/>
Next day it wasn't in, but instead an
<foreign xml:lang="fr">entrefilet</foreign>
<lb facs="#facs_3_r1l31" n="N028"/>
saying that all news about hostilities in
<placeName ref="#place-7002294">Anatolia</placeName>
<lb facs="#facs_3_r1l32" n="N029"/>
had been taken verbatim from English, Indian, Egyptian
<lb facs="#facs_3_r1l33" n="N030"/>
+ other papers. I had just read this, in a passion
<lb facs="#facs_3_r1l34" n="N031"/>
which words fail me to describe, when who should
</ab>
<pb facs="#facs_4" n="4" xml:id="img_0004"/>
<ab facs="#facs_4_r1">
<lb facs="#facs_4_r1l1" n="N001"/>
come in but the luckless editor of the Dijlah. I thanked
<lb facs="#facs_4_r1l2" n="N002"/>
God for a fair command of Arabic. Mentioning to him
<lb facs="#facs_4_r1l3" n="N003"/>
among other matters that he was carrion I informed
<lb facs="#facs_4_r1l4" n="N004"/>
him that unless my paragraph were in next
<lb facs="#facs_4_r1l5" n="N005"/>
day's paper he would find himself in gaol. It was;
<lb facs="#facs_4_r1l6" n="N006"/>
together with a leader entitled: A Liberal attacked
<lb facs="#facs_4_r1l7" n="N007"/>
by Bastards, which was probably intended for me,
<lb facs="#facs_4_r1l8" n="N008"/>
though it naturally didn't say so. That leaves me
<lb facs="#facs_4_r1l9" n="N009"/>
perfectly cold, however. The main thing is that that
<lb facs="#facs_4_r1l10" n="N010"/>
young man will have some difficulty in reconciling
<lb facs="#facs_4_r1l11" n="N011"/>
what I've made him publish with any stale news
<lb facs="#facs_4_r1l12" n="N012"/>
he may get from elsewhere.
<lb facs="#facs_4_r1l13" n="N013"/>
Lord! they do talk tosh. One of the subjects that even the
<lb facs="#facs_4_r1l14" n="N014"/>
best of them are fond of expatiating upon is the crying
<lb facs="#facs_4_r1l15" n="N015"/>
need for Democracy in
<placeName ref="#place-1000118">'Iraq</placeName>
-
<foreign xml:lang="ar">al damokratiyah</foreign>
<lb facs="#facs_4_r1l16" n="N016"/>
you find it on every page. I let them run on, knowing
<lb facs="#facs_4_r1l17" n="N017"/>
full well that
<persName ref="#person-EH001">Faisal</persName>
intends to be king in fact, not
<lb facs="#facs_4_r1l18" n="N018"/>
merely in name; + he is quite right. But the other
<lb facs="#facs_4_r1l19" n="N019"/>
day a young gentleman from
<placeName ref="#place-7002471">Mosul</placeName>
who designs to starts.
<lb facs="#facs_4_r1l20" n="N020"/>
a paper there asked me to draw him up some
<lb facs="#facs_4_r1l21" n="N021"/>
<gap reason="illegible"/>
directions for the guidance of the press. I did,
<lb facs="#facs_4_r1l22" n="N022"/>
with a will, + produced a minor masterpiece - with
<lb facs="#facs_4_r1l23" n="N023"/>
the more pleasure because I sent a copy to Faisal, who
<lb facs="#facs_4_r1l24" n="N024"/>
was delighted. I mentioned incidentally that in my
<lb facs="#facs_4_r1l25" n="N025"/>
opinion it would be easy to exaggerate the value of
<lb facs="#facs_4_r1l26" n="N026"/>
<foreign xml:lang="ar">al damakratiyah</foreign>
in this country; I didn't think that
<lb facs="#facs_4_r1l27" n="N027"/>
the
<seg type="editorialNote-target-text">
shaikhs
<note type="editorial">Honorific title meaning 'Elder', used for leaders of tribes and royal family members.</note>
</seg>
of the
<seg type="editorialNote-target-text">
Shibi
<note type="editorial">The Shibil tribe is one of many tribes within Iraq, some of which pre-date Islam. For centuries, tribes were the primary form of social organization through much of the Arabian Peninsula and tribal traditions remain culturally important in the region today.</note>
</seg>
, the Ghazalat + other
<lb facs="#facs_4_r1l28" n="N028"/>
Mesopotamian tribes whose names would occur
<lb facs="#facs_4_r1l29" n="N029"/>
to my young friend, had thoroughly mastered
<lb facs="#facs_4_r1l30" n="N030"/>
democratic principles. Until they had, etc etc.
</ab>
<pb facs="#facs_5" n="5" xml:id="img_0005"/>
<ab facs="#facs_5_r1">
<lb facs="#facs_5_r1l1" n="N001"/>
3. That's about all my news, except that yesterday
<lb facs="#facs_5_r1l2" n="N002"/>
I swam the
<placeName ref="#place-1130850">Tigris</placeName>
- not much of a feat you'll rightly
<lb facs="#facs_5_r1l3" n="N003"/>
observe, but the current is very strong in places.
<lb facs="#facs_5_r1l4" n="N004"/>
Bathing
<hi style="text-decoration: underline;">is</hi>
nice - it's the only nice thing in this weather.
<lb facs="#facs_5_r1l5" n="N005"/>
Sorry to say there are sharks in the Tigris; they haven't
<lb facs="#facs_5_r1l6" n="N006"/>
yet been reported higher than the mouth of the Diyalah
<lb facs="#facs_5_r1l7" n="N007"/>
where one bit an Arab boy this week.
<lb facs="#facs_5_r1l8" n="N008"/>
Oh, you should see
<persName ref="#person-EH016">Lady Cox</persName>
playing at leap frog in
<lb facs="#facs_5_r1l9" n="N009"/>
the water! - a game we indulge in.
<lb facs="#facs_5_r1l10" n="N010"/>
<persName ref="#person-EH006">Father</persName>
, do you think you could scrape up enough
<lb facs="#facs_5_r1l11" n="N011"/>
money to send me same more paper like this? It's so
<lb facs="#facs_5_r1l12" n="N012"/>
very nice to write on + so thin. I write you such long
<lb facs="#facs_5_r1l13" n="N013"/>
letters that I'm nearing the end of the stock you gave me.
<lb facs="#facs_5_r1l14" n="N014"/>
I have your letter of July 13 with the account of the
<lb facs="#facs_5_r1l15" n="N015"/>
<seg type="editorialNote-target-text">
Richmond ceremony
<note type="editorial">The unveiling of a Celtic cross in the town of Richmond, England. The cross was unveiled by her Father, Sir Hugh Bell, and was erected in memory of the Green Howards, also known as the Yorkshire regiment, who fought in the First World War.</note>
</seg>
which must have been very touching;
<lb facs="#facs_5_r1l16" n="N016"/>
also the delightful correspondence between you +
<lb facs="#facs_5_r1l17" n="N017"/>
<persName ref="#person-EH118">Frederic Harrison</persName>
. He is a remarkable old thing, is
<lb facs="#facs_5_r1l18" n="N018"/>
not he? for that matter, though not so old,
<lb facs="#facs_5_r1l19" n="N019"/>
so are you, bless you.
<lb facs="#facs_5_r1l20" n="N020"/>
<delSpan rend="strikethrough" spanTo="#facs_5_r1l26"/>
Oh Father I am so sick of
<persName ref="#person-EH078">Rosita Forbes</persName>
!
<lb facs="#facs_5_r1l21" n="N021"/>
+ the thing that makes me sickest is that she
<lb facs="#facs_5_r1l22" n="N022"/>
scarcely ever alludes to that capital boy,
<lb facs="#facs_5_r1l23" n="N023"/>
<persName ref="#person-EH119">Hasanain</persName>
, who was with her, an Egyptian
<lb facs="#facs_5_r1l24" n="N024"/>
without whom she couldn't have done anything.
<lb facs="#facs_5_r1l25" n="N025"/>
She doesn't know a word of Arabic. Well, as I
<lb facs="#facs_5_r1l26" n="N026"/>
say,
<seg type="editorialNote-target-text">
Dunya!
<anchor facs="#facs_5_r1l26"/>
<note type="editorial">An Islamic term referring to the earthly world and its possessions, as opposed to the spiritual world and the hereafter.</note>
</seg>
<lb facs="#facs_5_r1l28" n="N027"/>
<delSpan rend="strikethrough" spanTo="#facs_6_r1l6"/>
